<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF109-713-813  </DOCNO><DOCID>09 713 813.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>LAN Times  Dec 10 1990 v7 n15 p83(3).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>David Williams reveals strategy at Intel: networking 'visionary'takes on new 'mission' after Banyan, Novell. (interview)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Breidenbach, Susan.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>David Williams, strategic marketing manager for Intel's PersonalComputer Enhancement Operation's (PCEO) network enhancementbusiness, is considered something of a visionary in the local areanetwork (LAN) industry.andP;  Intel hired Williams away from BanyanSystems; prior to that, he had worked at Novell, first in OEMmarketing, then moving to strategic marketing.andP;  Williams discussesthat shift and his tendency to want to move on as soon as he feelshe has accomplished what he set out to do at a particular company.andO;Williams expects Intel PCEO to pursue development ofapplication-specific server platforms, but declines to discuss thelikelihood of it entering the network adapter market.andP;  Williamsbelieves the networking industry will do better than the rest ofthe computer industry in the case of a recession.andP;  Williamsexpects Banyan Systems to continue to do well in its niche for thefuture.andP;  Williams also discusses the network operating systemsmarket, his approach to strategic planning, and what the 1990shold for the computer industry.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   Intel Corp. Personal Computer Enhancement Operation (Officials andemployees).andO;Ticker:    INTC.andO;Topic:     InterviewStrategic PlanningMarketing StrategyManagement Style.andO;Feature:   illustrationportrait.andO;Caption:   David Williams. (portrait)Person:    Williams, David (Interviews).andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>